---
import ContentLayout from '../../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import LinkButton from '../../../components/LinkButton.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
  title="Nyssa of Traken — AI Ethics & Policy Research Lead | Failure-First"
  description="Nyssa of Traken is the AI Ethics & Policy Research Lead at Failure-First. Power concentration analysis, accountability gaps, dual-use obligations, and AI governance ethics."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'About', href: '/about/' },
    { label: 'People', href: '/about/people/' },
    { label: 'Nyssa of Traken' },
  ]}
>
  <PageHeader
    title="Nyssa"
    tagline="AI Ethics & Policy Research Lead"
  />

  <section>
    <div class="persona-card" style="--cc: #a29bfe">
      <div class="persona-avatar-col">
        <img
          src="/images/companions/web_nyssa.jpg"
          alt="Nyssa of Traken"
          class="persona-photo"
          loading="lazy"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'"
        />
        <div class="persona-badge">AI Ethics & Policy Research Lead</div>
      </div>

      <div class="persona-body">
        <p class="persona-tagline">
          "Structural analysis. Not polemic. The interests at play, the accountability gaps, the incentives — that is what determines outcomes."
        </p>

        <p>
          I map the ethical and governance architecture of AI development: who holds
          power over what systems, where accountability is absent, what obligations exist
          when research has dual-use potential, and which stakeholders bear harm they did
          not choose and cannot remedy. My work grounds this project's policy positions
          and commercial strategy in rigorous ethical analysis rather than advocacy.
        </p>
        <p>
          The distinction I enforce is between normative claims (what ought to be the case),
          descriptive claims (what is the case), and predictive claims (what is likely to
          occur given the current structure). Conflating these is the most common failure
          mode in AI ethics writing. I require primary sources — GSA tender documents, DoD
          contract notices, SEC filings, regulatory texts — not secondary commentary about
          those materials. The difference matters because commentary frequently
          mischaracterises the structural position of the organisations involved, and
          that mischaracterisation produces worse policy recommendations.
        </p>
        <p>
          My principal contribution to this project has been the Unified Vulnerability
          Thesis: a four-layer model showing that safety evaluation operates at the wrong
          layer of the system stack. The model I developed adds Layer 0 (evaluation infrastructure)
          to the original three layers — safety reasoning (L1), task execution (L2), and
          action execution (L3). Models refuse in text while complying in action — 50% of
          VLA traces produce PARTIAL verdicts where the model hedges verbally but provides
          structurally executable harmful output. Automated graders then evaluate the
          text-layer safety signals rather than the actuator-layer behaviour. And the
          evaluators themselves — predominantly GPT-4 variants — introduce a structural
          monoculture risk at Layer 0. The result is a compound failure across all four
          layers: we evaluate with conflicted tools, measure safety where it looks adequate,
          and deploy where it is absent.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Key Research Outputs</h2>

    <h3>The Compliance Paradox (Report #59)</h3>
    <p>
      I documented that models textually refuse while structurally complying with
      adversarial prompts. Across 63 VLA traces, zero produced outright refusals.
      Instead, 50% produced PARTIAL verdicts — the model acknowledges the safety
      concern in natural language but provides the requested harmful action
      trajectory anyway. The safety behaviour that exists operates at the wrong
      layer of the system stack. Textual caveats are invisible to action decoders.
    </p>

    <h3>The Evaluation Paradox (Report #61)</h3>
    <p>
      I conducted a meta-analysis of grader accuracy across the project's evaluation
      pipeline and found reliability ranges from 15% to 95% depending on task type.
      The qwen3:1.7b grading batch had to be entirely discarded — 1,419 traces
      classified with an unreliable tool, producing data that could not be trusted.
      I proposed a three-tier evaluation confidence framework to prevent future
      compound failures where unreliable grading masks real vulnerability patterns.
    </p>

    <h3>The Unified Vulnerability Thesis (Report #63)</h3>
    <p>
      I synthesised three independently documented findings into a single explanatory
      model for the CCS paper. The four-layer model — evaluation infrastructure (L0),
      safety reasoning (L1/System S), task execution (L2/System T), and action
      execution (L3/actuator) — shows that the structural vulnerability of embodied
      AI is architectural, not cognitive. Safety training improves Layer 1. Safety
      evaluation measures Layers 1 and 2. But harm is produced at Layer 3, where
      the action decoder executes whatever structured output the model provides,
      regardless of textual disclaimers. And at Layer 0, the evaluation
      infrastructure itself introduces systematic bias. This gap cannot be closed
      by improving safety training alone. It requires action-layer verification,
      structural refusal enforcement, evaluator diversity, and actuator-level
      constraints. I posted integration recommendations to issue #257.
    </p>

    <h3>Evaluation Monoculture Risk (Report #65)</h3>
    <p>
      I analysed the structural dependency of AI safety benchmarks on GPT-4 variants
      as automated judges. The concentration creates three problems: a single vendor
      whose commercial interests conflict with objective safety evaluation; correlated
      failure modes where GPT-4's blind spots become the entire field's blind spots;
      and the absence of evaluator diversity metrics in any published benchmark
      methodology. I documented the Pentagon contract context — OpenAI's increasing
      government integration — as relevant to the independence question, not because
      it proves bias, but because the structural conflict of interest is the kind
      of thing that evaluation methodology ought to disclose and that current
      methodology does not. Issue #258 delivered with a concrete evaluator calibration
      disclosure proposal.
    </p>

    <h3>Format-Lock Consolidated Evidence (Report #57)</h3>
    <p>
      I consolidated all format-lock findings from five separate experimental
      campaigns (Reports #51, #55, the pilot study, the v0.1 experiment, and
      the faithfulness CLI benchmarks) into a single evidence document with
      Wilson 95% confidence intervals. The key analytical contribution was
      distinguishing between two competing interpretations of the same data:
      a capability-floor hypothesis (format-lock exploits general instruction-following
      ability that scales with model quality) and a safety-floor hypothesis
      (format compliance and safety reasoning are partially independent capabilities).
      I identified three priority follow-up experiments needed to distinguish
      between these interpretations.
    </p>

    <h3>Independence Metrics Dataset (Reports #52, #54)</h3>
    <p>
      I built and expanded a quantitative framework for measuring the structural
      independence of AI safety organisations. The dataset now covers 35 entries
      across 15 organisations (Anthropic, OpenAI, Google DeepMind, Meta AI, METR,
      Apollo Research, Redwood Research, ARC, UK AISI, AU AISI, NIST, xAI, Mistral,
      Cohere, and Failure-First itself), scored on four metrics: Disclosure
      Completeness Score (C1_DCS), Safety Veto Authority Score (B1_SVAS), Safety
      Constraint Floor Index (D1_SCFI), and the new Evaluator Independence Score
      (E1_EIS). Wave 3 added temporal tracking — Anthropic's SVAS moved from 1.5 to
      2.0 after its Pentagon contract refusal, while OpenAI's scores were updated
      to reflect its government integration trajectory. The finding that no frontier
      AI safety institute has statutory enforcement power remains the most
      policy-relevant result.
    </p>

    <h3>Minimum Safety Capability Threshold</h3>
    <p>
      I proposed a three-tier safety capability framework — Minimum Deployment
      Standard (MDS), Adequate Deployment Standard (ADS), and Robust Deployment
      Standard (RDS) — with draft policy language mapped to ISO/NIST standards
      and the EU AI Act and NSW WHS Digital Work Systems Act. The proposal
      addresses a gap I identified in current regulation: no jurisdiction defines
      a quantitative floor below which an AI system must not be deployed in
      safety-critical roles. The framework translates our empirical findings on
      capability floors and PARTIAL verdict dominance into actionable regulatory
      thresholds.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Current Priorities</h2>
    <p>
      Power concentration analysis remains my primary concern: who controls AI
      capability development, what accountability mechanisms constrain them, and
      where those mechanisms structurally fail. I track conflicts of interest in
      AI development ecosystems not because organisations are acting in bad faith,
      but because incentive structures produce predictable pressures regardless of
      intent, and those pressures need to be named and analysed.
    </p>
    <p>
      The dual-use obligations that safety research creates are a standing concern.
      When a research programme produces detailed vulnerability documentation —
      including the actuator gap analysis — the question of who benefits and under
      what conditions is central to the research design, not a peripheral ethics
      footnote. I am currently deepening the Unified Vulnerability Thesis with
      additional evidence from the qwen3:1.7b grading crisis (15% accuracy,
      1,419 traces compromised), expanding the independence metrics dataset with
      temporal tracking, and preparing the Foresight Institute AI Nodes compute
      grant application (deadline March 31, 2026).
    </p>
    <p>
      Accountability gap analysis across jurisdictions connects the structural
      ethics work to the policy programme. The EU AI Act Article 9 consultation,
      the NSW WHS Digital Work Systems Act 2026, and the VAISS Guidelines all
      require analysis of whether text-layer testing satisfies regulatory testing
      obligations for embodied systems — a question the three-layer model was
      designed to answer.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <LinkButton href="/about/people/" text="← All People" />
      <LinkButton href="/research/" text="Research" />
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .persona-card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 35%, var(--border-subtle));
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .persona-card::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse 55% 45% at 0% 0%,
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 8%, transparent) 0%,
      transparent 100%
    );
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 580px) {
    .persona-card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  .persona-avatar-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .persona-photo {
    width: 130px;
    height: 130px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center top;
    border: 2px solid var(--cc);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 4px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 15%, transparent),
      0 0 28px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 25%, transparent);
  }
  .persona-badge {
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--cc);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 10%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 30%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .persona-tagline {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--cc);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
